---
export const prerender = true;

import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';

export function getStaticPaths() {
  return [{ params: { lang: 'en' } }, { params: { lang: 'zh' } }];
}

const { lang } = Astro.params;

const content = {
  en: {
    title: "Hello, I'm <span class=\"accent\">Daniel</span>.",
    tagline: 'Entrepreneur · Researcher · Builder',
    sections: [
      {
        heading: 'I treat the world as a laboratory.',
        body: [
          "It sounds a little like the sort of motto you might write on the cover of a notebook, but it is genuinely close to the way I have lived these past years. Some people turn life into a CV. I have more often turned mine into fieldwork. To me, the world is not a map waiting to be ticked off, nor a set of standard answers waiting to be memorised, but a vast, complicated, often bewildering scene that is all the more fascinating for it. You can study it, take part in it, question it, and sometimes be taught a lesson by it in return.",
          "Over the years, I have built products, written code, started businesses, and moved back and forth between different cities and countries. I have been through internal ventures, and I once incorporated a company in Singapore with full blood and fire. I once stood on stages across Japan, Singapore, and other countries, speaking to hundreds of audiences, and also took the stage at UC Berkeley. I graduated from the Institute for Entrepreneurship and Strategy at Lancaster University Management School, and I spent a year and a half living in the UK. During that time, I loved going to the Lake District and lying on the grass watching the clouds. Coming at things from the angles of research and business, I began to think more seriously about entrepreneurship, organisations, choice, and the way the world works. As time has gone on, I have felt more and more that these experiences, scattered as they may seem, have all been circling the same question: how do people make sense of the world, and how do we find our place in an age that seems just a little overenthusiastic about change?",
          "My work history is not exactly straightforward.\nI am a cross-border entrepreneur, and I have also long been a senior software engineer, technology consultant, and product builder.\nI talk about software and I talk about business; I can hold my own in AI, and I have written blockchain smart contracts; I have long remained curious about products, markets, strategy, investing, and the internet's shifting terrain. Put all of those labels together and, now and then, they can look like a self-introduction built by someone who knows their way round keywords. But what truly interests me has never been the labels themselves. It is the more fundamental question beneath them: where is technology taking people? And in a world that refreshes itself at speed, how do we avoid living like a browser tab stuck on perpetual reload?",
        ],
      },
      {
        heading: 'Seventy countries and counting.',
        body: [
          "I have also travelled and lived across more than seventy countries.\nNot because I wanted to turn my passport into a loyalty card, and not because I have any particular fondness for dragging a suitcase through an airport. It is simply that once you have gone far enough, you begin to realise that travel has never really been about scenery alone. It feels more like changing coordinate systems again and again.",
          "You see entirely different ways of living, understand that the world can in fact be assembled in all sorts of versions, and, as a result, allow some necessary looseness into the things you once took for granted. Very often, travel does not take you away from yourself. It returns you to yourself, and lets you discover that the life you once thought of as obvious was only one version among many.",
        ],
      },
      {
        heading: 'Beyond technology.',
        body: [
          "Beyond technology, products, entrepreneurship, and investing, I also love words, and the books and films that are willing to look life directly in the eye. I read books on method, and I read philosophy and literature; I care about trends, and I care about people; I want to understand how the world works, and I also want to understand why someone might be struck by a poem late at night and suddenly find tears in their eyes. Sanmao, Maugham, Hermann Hesse, Pessoa, Li Juan, Haruki Murakami, Milan Kundera, Camus, and Schopenhauer have all accompanied me at different moments along certain inner roads. More than standard answers, I find myself drawn to questions of existence, absurdity, freedom, and solitude.",
          "I keep trying to live with awareness.\nI am the sort of person who looks up at the moon without forgetting the sixpence.\nI love thought, but I also love the feeling of letting the body meet the world directly. In ordinary life, I go hiking, camping, surfing, surfskating, and diving, and I am always drawn to trying different kinds of adventure. To me, being alive is not only about understanding the world. It is also about feeling it first-hand.",
        ],
      },
      {
        heading: 'This Blog',
        body: [
          "So this blog, to me, is not merely a place to put articles.\nIt is more like a long table, a logbook, or a letter that has grown very long and still has no intention of ending.",
          "Here, I want to share knowledge, perspective, and thought; to record the process of entrepreneurship and building products; to gather my observations on AI, business, investing, travel, books, and writing; and also to talk about slower things, harder things to measure, but things that matter all the same: the feeling of being alive, the human condition, the weight of choice, and how we might live without betraying ourselves. I see this as part of my personal brand, but I hope it is not a shop window. I hope it is a place with some warmth in it. The world already has plenty of beautifully packaged words. What feels truly scarce is something sincere, interesting, and capable of making a person pause and think.",
          "The knowledge carried in every post on this blog comes from years of accumulated learning, research notes, lived experience, reflection, and mistakes gathered across two ventures I have been through. The articles themselves are currently drafted by my AI agent, Kotonoha, then edited, assembled, and published by Rio. Even after humanising, they still carry a faint AI texture at the moment. For now, that is a compromise I am willing to make so that I can organise what I know into proper pieces in the shortest possible time. If a service emerges later that can genuinely write in my own voice, cadence, and tone, I intend to update the entire archive in one go. I appreciate your patience with that in the meantime.",
          "I hope that the people who read this will meet someone like this:\nSomeone a little rational, and a little romantic.\nSomeone who can take a product apart and still be moved by a poem.\nSomeone who can talk about markets, technology, strategy, and the future, and who is also willing to talk about people, freedom, and how to preserve one's capacity to feel in the midst of ordinary life.\nSomeone who has seen a little of the world and still has not stopped being curious about it.",
          "This is a place not only for trends, but for how to live.\nNot only for tools, but for people.\nNot only for efficiency, but for the inner life.\nNot only for distant places, but for the things that are difficult to name and yet have been felt by everyone.",
        ],
      },
      {
        heading: 'Come by sometime?',
        body: [
          "I want to leave behind thought, connect with kindred spirits, make sense of the world, and leave a path for my future self, a path back to where my original intentions began. Here, I remember the past and think about eternity. And along the way, I hope to meet more people too.",
          "If you are curious about the world, hungry for knowledge, sensitive to life, or merely passing through and would like to talk about entrepreneurship, AI, products, travel, books, poetry, and life, you are very welcome to get in touch.",
          "I have always believed that the meeting of one person and another is one of the most romantic things in the world, and one of the most worthwhile subjects of study.",
        ],
        socials: [
          { label: 'LinkedIn', href: 'https://www.linkedin.com/in/huanghuaihsuan/' },
        ],
      },
    ],
  },
  zh: {
    title: "嗨，我是 <span class=\"accent\">Daniel</span>。",
    tagline: '創業者 · 研究者 · 建構者',
    sections: [
      {
        heading: '我把世界當實驗室。',
        body: [
          "這句話聽起來有點像寫在筆記本封面上的座右銘，但它確實很接近我這些年活著的方式。有人把人生過成履歷，我比較常把它過成田野調查。對我來說，世界不是一張等著打卡的地圖，也不是一套等待背熟的標準答案，而是一個巨大、複雜、時常令人困惑，卻也因此迷人的現場。你可以研究它，參與它，質疑它，偶爾也被它反過來教育。",
          "這些年，我做過產品、寫過程式、創過業，也在不同城市和國家之間來回移動。我經歷過內部創業，也曾熱血沸騰地在新加坡成立公司法人。我曾在日本、新加坡等多國的舞臺上面對數百位聽眾，也曾在加州大學柏克萊分校的講台上分享。我畢業於蘭卡斯特大學管理學院創業與戰略研究所，曾在英國生活一年半。那段時間，我很喜歡去湖區，躺在草地上看雲。從研究與商業的角度出發，我更認真地理解創業、組織、選擇與世界運作的方式。一路走來，我愈來愈覺得，那些看起來分散的經歷，其實都在回答同一個問題：人怎麼理解世界，又怎麼在這個變動得有點過分積極的時代裡，找到自己的位置。",
          "我的工作經歷不算單純。\n我是跨國創業者，也一直是資深軟體工程師、科技顧問與產品建造者。\n我談軟體技術，也談商業；談得來 AI，也寫過區塊鏈智能合約；對產品、市場、策略、投資，以及網路世界的變化一直很好奇。這些名詞放在一起，偶爾看起來像一份很會使用關鍵字的自我介紹，但我真正感興趣的，從來不是名詞本身，而是它們背後那個更根本的問題：科技會把人帶去哪裡？我們又該怎麼在快速更新的世界裡，不把自己活成一個不停刷新頁面的瀏覽器分頁？",
        ],
      },
      {
        heading: '七十多個國家的視野。',
        body: [
          "我也曾在七十多個國家之間旅行與生活。\n這不是為了把護照蓋成集點卡，也不是因為我對拖著行李箱衝機場這件事有特殊癖好。只是走得夠遠之後，你會慢慢明白，旅行從來不只是風景的問題，它更像是在不斷更換座標系統。",
          "你會看見截然不同的生活方式，理解世界原來可以被組裝成那麼多版本，也會因此對自己原本深信不疑的東西，產生一些必要的鬆動。很多時候，旅行不是把人帶去遠方，而是把人送回自己身上，讓你重新發現，原來你一直以為理所當然的生活，也只是一種版本而已。",
        ],
      },
      {
        heading: '在科技之上。',
        body: [
          "除了科技、產品、創業與投資，我也喜歡文字，喜歡那些願意直視生命的書與電影。我讀方法論，也讀哲學與文學；我關心趨勢，也關心人類；我想理解世界怎麼運作，也想理解，一個人為什麼會在深夜被一首詩擊中，忽然泛淚。三毛、毛姆、赫曼赫塞、佩索亞、李娟、村上春樹、米蘭．昆德拉、卡繆、叔本華，都曾在不同的時刻陪我走過一些內在的路。比起標準答案，我更常被存在、荒誕、自由、孤獨這些題目吸引。",
          "我一直試著有意識地活著。\n我是個抬頭看見月亮，也不忘六便士的人。\n我喜歡思想，也喜歡身體與世界真實接觸的感覺。平常我會登山、露營、衝浪、衝浪滑板、潛水，也想嘗試各種冒險。對我來說，活著不只是理解世界，也是親身去感受它。",
        ],
      },
      {
        heading: '關於這個部落格',
        body: [
          "所以這個部落格，對我來說，不只是放文章的地方。\n它比較像一張長桌，一本航海日誌，或者一封寫得很長很長，還不打算停筆的信。",
          "我想在這裡分享知識、眼界與思考，記錄創業與做產品的過程，整理我對 AI、商業、投資、旅行、書與文字的觀察，也談一些更慢、更不容易量化，卻始終重要的東西，像是生命感、人的處境、選擇的重量，還有我們究竟該怎麼活，才不算辜負自己。我把它當成個人品牌的一部分，但我希望它不是一個展示櫥窗，而是一個有溫度的地方。畢竟這個世界已經有很多包裝得很好的話，真正稀缺的，反而是真誠、有趣、能讓人停下來想一想的東西。",
          "這個部落格每篇文章裡所傳達的知識，來自我這些年經歷兩次創業之後，經年累月累積下來的學習、研究筆記、親身經驗、思考與踩過的坑。只是目前這些文章，是由我的 AI agent 言葉代筆，再由理央編寫、整理與推送。雖然已經做過 Humanizer 處理，但現在讀起來多少還是會有一點 AI 味。為了在最短時間內把這些知識整理成篇，這是我目前接受的一項折衷。等未來真的出現能用我的聲紋、語氣與節奏去寫作的 AI 服務時，我會再把整個文章庫一次更新；這部分，還請你多包涵。",
          "我希望讀這裡的人，會遇見一個這樣的我：\n一個有點理性，也有點浪漫的人。\n一個會拆解產品，也會被詩打動的人。\n一個可以談市場、技術、策略與未來，也願意談人、談自由、談怎麼在生活裡保留感受力的人。\n一個看過一些世界，也還沒有停止對世界好奇的人。",
          "這裡不只談趨勢，也談怎麼活。\n不只談工具，也談人。\n不只談效率，也談內心。\n不只談遠方，也談那些說不清、但每個人都曾經感受過的事。",
        ],
      },
      {
        heading: '來串門子？',
        body: [
          "我想留下思考，連結同類，整理世界，也替未來的自己留一條路，一條回得去初心的路。在這裡，我懷念過去，也思考永恆。而在這條路上，我也希望能結識更多人。",
          "若你也對世界有好奇，對知識有胃口，對生命有感覺，或者只是剛好路過這裡，想聊聊創業、AI、產品、旅行、書、詩與人生，都很歡迎來找我聊聊。",
          "我一直深信著，人和人的相遇，本身就是世界最浪漫、最值得研究的事之一。",
        ],
        socials: [
          { label: 'LinkedIn', href: 'https://www.linkedin.com/in/huanghuaihsuan/' },
        ],
      },
    ],
  },
};

const c = content[lang as 'en' | 'zh'];
---

<Base title="About — danielcanfly" description="About Daniel." lang={lang!}>
  <Header currentLang={lang} />

  <main class="about-main">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="about-grid">
        <header class="about-header animate-in">
          <h1 class="about-title" set:html={c.title}></h1>
          <p class="about-tagline">{c.tagline}</p>
        </header>

        <div class="about-content animate-in animate-delay-1">
          {c.sections.map(section => (
            <section class="about-section">
              <h2>{section.heading}</h2>
              {section.body && Array.isArray(section.body) && section.body.map(para => (
                <p class="about-prose" set:html={para}></p>
              ))}
              {section.socials && (
                <div class="social-links">
                  {section.socials.map(s => (
                    <a href={s.href} target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="social-link">
                      {s.label}
                    </a>
                  ))}
                </div>
              )}
            </section>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Base>

<style>
  .about-main {
    padding: var(--space-10) 0;
  }

  .about-grid {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .about-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .about-title {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3rem);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .about-tagline {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-muted);
  }

  .about-content {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-8);
  }

  .about-section h2 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
  }

  .about-prose {
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.85;
    max-width: 100%;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .about-prose:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .social-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-2);
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
  }

  .social-link {
    padding: 8px 16px;
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-text);
    transition: all var(--transition-fast);
  }

  .social-link:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }
</style>
